Beijing's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wildlife cities to "settle down" -Chinanews.com
2020-07-26 05: 03: 17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The natural ecology of the capital continues to improve, attracting wildlife cities to "settle down"
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
(Reporter Wang Bin) A reporter from Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Bureau of Landscaping and Greening that in recent years, with the continuous improvement of the capital's natural ecological environment, the species and number of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals inhabiting Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including national first-class protected animals such as brown pheasant and black stork, as well as national second-class protected animals such as impala, swan, gray crane and mandarin duck.
Whether it is planted into urban forests everywhere in the Second Ring Road or embedded in small and micro wetlands between buildings, it not only brings the wild interest of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In midsummer, Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of vitality.
A raccoon dog was playing leisurely by the mountain stream, while two badgers were fighting with each other.
Looking back, a wild boar couldn't help scratching his body and was rubbing against the bark. Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Management Office, said that by the end of 2019, there were 178 species of wild animals living in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, including the national first-class protected animal golden eagle and the national second-class protected animal spoon chicken and impala. Nearly one third of the wild animal species in the city can be found here.
"In Songshan, wild animals are the real 'masters', and our staff can only be regarded as the 'bodyguards' of others at best."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the situation of wildlife in the reserve on the spot, more than 30 professional patrol members patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day, and there will be a "big circle" every month, spending a whole day almost all over the reserve.
"During inspections, we should not only check and record biodiversity, but also check and install artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install field infrared cameras, and so on."
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli introduced that with the continuous enrichment of biodiversity in the reserve in recent years, more and more wild animals appear in the camera, leopard cats, raccoon dogs and pig badgers have become "resident guests," and the "appearance rate" of impala, a national second-class protected animal, is also getting higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, director of the Wildlife and Wetland Protection Division of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Landscaping and Greening, said that the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 in 1994 to more than 500 now, and the species and number of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
Wild animals are becoming more and more common in cities, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of greening in capital cities in recent years.
In particular, the new round of afforestation and greening construction of one million mu that began in 2018 proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological function of woodland and green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature."
The planning strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green space, so as to facilitate wild animals to "visit relatives and friends," and the trees planted are also honey and food plants that animals love.



















































































Black land "grows" agricultural modernization-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, July 26. Title: Black land "grows" agricultural modernization
In midsummer, two spraying planes passed by the 10,000-mu high-yield demonstration field in the second operation station of the fifth management area of Friendship Farm, forming two white lines. The characters "the first field in the world" planted with black rice seedlings in the green fields were particularly eye-catching.
Kong Lingqiang, the head of the operation station, said that this kind of plane can spray drugs on more than 6,000 mu of cultivated land a day, and its efficiency is about 8 times that of unmanned aerial vehicles and hundreds of times that of manual labor.
This farm is located in Youyi County, Heilongjiang Province, China's largest grain-producing province. From the sound of rice cutting in the past to the sound of rumbling now, traditional Chinese farming and farms have transformed in this black soil belt.
In addition to airplanes, satellites are also used in modern agricultural production at Friendship Farm.
Kong Lingqiang introduced that on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve precise fertilization, reduce agricultural investment and reduce pollution; on the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the standardized operation level of agricultural machinery in the field.
In the process of rice production this year, the farm expanded the operating area of satellite navigation unmanned transplanting technology from 3,000 mu last year to 30,000 mu.
This technology makes seedling planting more uniform, maximizes the utilization of sunlight and cultivated land resources, and saves labor costs of 16 yuan per mu.
Farms try new technologies such as informatization and intelligence in agricultural production, forming the largest agricultural machinery group in China from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, at present, the total number of farm machinery is 49,000 units (pieces), and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field is 99.8%.
Agricultural machinery operations achieve 100% GPS satellite navigation, 100% precision sowing in dry fields, and 100% high-power locomotive operations in dry fields.
"Green agriculture, smart agriculture and digital agriculture are the exploration direction of agricultural modernization."
Liu Hualian, director of Friendship Farm, said.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
In recent years, Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation, represented by farms, has played a leading role in demonstrating and leading the "aircraft carrier" of modern agriculture, and has initially established a modern agricultural industrial system dominated by large-scale planting, standardized production and industrialized management.
In the suburb of Youyi County, there is an agricultural machinery Expo Park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
More than 140 sets (pieces) of agricultural machinery introduced and used by Heilongjiang Reclamation over the years are on display here.
These agricultural machinery and farms have witnessed the development of China's agricultural modernization.
Give up a small family for everyone-Anhui Hefei Jiangkou River Lianwei Mass Transfer Direct Attack-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26 (Xinhua) Title: Give up small family for everyone-Anhui Hefei Jiangkou River Lianwei Mass Transfer Direct Attack
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu and Liu Xia Village
At 4 o'clock in the afternoon on July 25, Fu Kunbao, wearing mud-covered rubber shoes, went from the front room to the back room, and his wife Zhou Yan was busy packing things back and forth.
"I received a call from the village cadre to transfer, and I was still weeding in the field."
Fu Kunbao said that he transferred more than 60 mu of land and planted rice, and now he is growing well. "I took medicine yesterday, and I haven't cleaned up my tools."
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner. "No one wants to be flooded at home, let's give up a small home for everyone."
In response to the continuous high water level pressure and possible heavy rainfall in Chaohu Lake, Hefei City, Anhui Province is preparing to open the Jiangkou River Lianwei, where Fu Kunbao's family is located, for flood diversion and storage on the 26th.
Jiangkou River Lianwei is located in Feixi County, close to Chaohu levee.
There are thousands of villagers involved in Yandian Township and Sanhe Town who need to be transferred.
As of 16: 00 on the 25th, the water level of Chaohu Lake, the fifth largest freshwater lake in China, remained at a high level of 13.2 meters, exceeding the guaranteed water level by 0.7 meters.
Fu Kunbao's kitchen is clean, with a pot of pumpkin head vegetables on the table, eggs and some gravy in the fridge.
"I didn't expect to move. The water in Jiangkou River looks good at present."
Zhou Yan said that the home is a bungalow, and some large objects have not yet been decided where to put them.
"Pack up your valuables first. Large items such as refrigerators and televisions can be temporarily placed in high-lying neighbors or relatives."
Wang Liwen, a village cadre, gave Fu Kunbao advice.
Wang Liwen was responsible for the transfer and resettlement of 13 villagers, and notified each household to confirm each person's resettlement plan.
The nearest settlement to Fu Kunbao's home is Su Primary School in Yandian Township, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to the big items, Fu Kunbao and his wife also have a headache of more than 1000 jin of grain and some newly bought furniture.
"The food is ready to be dragged to relatives' homes, and the furniture can't be moved."
After a discussion, the couple put a stool under the newly bought bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 p.m., Fu Kunbao began to transport things to relatives' homes by tricycle, and Zhou Yan continued to clean up at home.
At 11 o'clock in the evening, the couple watched it back and forth at home, turned on the switch, and prepared to go to the resettlement site.
"I hope the water will return soon."
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9: 30 a.m. on July 26, the reporter saw at the scene of Jiangkou River Lianwei that the local area had made various preparations before flood diversion.
