The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft registered in the United States, because the corrosion of the air check valves of the above passenger aircraft may cause the engine to stop in the air.
The FAA said that so far, it has received four reports of engine parking of 737NG and 737Classic passenger planes in the air, so it has made an emergency inspection request. The inspection targets are passenger planes that have been parked continuously for 7 days or more and passenger planes that have flown less than 11 times so far after re-entering the flight.
The FAA warned that if the stage 5 check valves of all two engines of the airliner are corroded, they may get stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to lose power completely and unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace this key component before the passenger plane is put into use again.
Boeing responded later that day that the COVID-19 outbreak had reduced travel demand, and many passenger planes had been sealed up or used less, and "check valves were more vulnerable to corrosion."
Boeing also said that it has advised airline operators to inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the order, and if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in overhauling and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that passenger planes owned by major US airline operators usually fly several times a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown epidemic, a large number of passenger planes have been grounded; with the recent slow growth of passenger travel demand, some passenger planes have been put into operation again.
The FAA did not release the details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its passenger planes was en route from Seattle, Washington to Austin, Texas on July 15 when an engine suddenly stopped, and the passenger plane finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the engine of the passenger plane and had inspected the engines of six passenger planes in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that their passenger planes did not have engine flameout associated with air check valves.
Four American Airlines aircraft will be inspected and 28 United Airlines aircraft will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 passenger planes, but did not say whether there had been engine flameout.
According to several media reports, the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another impact on Boeing.
A Boeing 737MAX passenger plane of Indonesian Lion Airlines and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing 346 people in total.
This series of passenger planes were subsequently grounded worldwide, stopped production in January this year, and resumed production in May.
FAA Director Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA "made a mistake" in the supervision of Boeing on the 737MAX passenger plane.
