Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to sue the school after being compensated for being smashed in the playground of the university?
2020-07-26 05: 01: 11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, and the child was compensated before suing the school
- our correspondent Zhao Yifan
Three-year-old Xiaowen was playing in the playground of a university when he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen Mou of the softball team while pitching.
After Chen made compensation, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiaowen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding an apology from the school where the playground occurred, and paying a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and mental damage.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Haidian District People's Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net on the playground at the time of the incident, which had fulfilled its appropriate security obligations, and Chen had made compensation, so the judgment rejected the plaintiff's claim.
Mr. Wen claimed that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiaowen to play on the school playground while the softball team was training on the playground.
In order to avoid the risks, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents moved in the safe area designated by the softball team.
But then Chen Mou, a softball team member, got rid of the ball while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the protective net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiaowen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that the facilities of the school stadium do not meet the relevant safety regulations and do not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The school's fault led to the above-mentioned events, which caused Xiaowen to suffer great physical and mental pain, and also brought great pain to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In response, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net on the playground, posted management regulations and training notices, told that entering the playground must keep a safe distance from the training ground and reminded people to pay attention to their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school "failed to fulfill its security obligations," so he did not agree to compensation.
After hearing the case, the court held that the site of the incident was open to the public free of charge by the university involved in the case. Although the school has a security obligation for the management of the playground, this security obligation only needs to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground, which has fulfilled its appropriate security obligations, and Chen Mou also compensated Xiaowen for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan according to the compensation agreement reached before. Both parties agreed to settle the dispute at one time.
Afterwards, Xiaowen's parents once again claimed compensation from the school, which was unfounded in law. The court ruled that all the plaintiff's claims were rejected.
After the verdict was pronounced, neither party appealed, and the verdict has now entered into force.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation of security; In the case that the third party's behavior causes damage to others, the third party shall bear tort liability, while the public place manager who fails to fulfill the obligation of security shall bear corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said that as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the whole place and foresee the possible dangers and damage, so he is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or reduce the degree of damage, and the cost of avoiding and reducing damage is the lowest, so the law stipulates that he shall bear the corresponding guarantee obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified people entering the playground open to the public free of charge, the school's security obligation should be compatible with its social activities. Specifically, it should mainly take basic security measures and have the obligation to inform hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation to inform, it can be concluded that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for third-party infringement, even if the managers of schools and other public places fail to fulfill their security obligations, their liability is also a supplement to damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, managers can also recover compensation from the third party after assuming supplementary liability.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victims should not expand the scope of claims after they have received compensation from the direct infringer.






































































