Understand what is the professional grade difference before volunteering to fill in the report-Zhongxin.com
2020-07-27 02: 22: 36 Source: Chongqing Morning Post Author: Yu Xiao Editor: Yu Xiao
Understand what is the professional grade difference before volunteering to fill in the report
Every year, there are students or parents who do not understand the terms involved in the voluntary filling, which affects the voluntary filling.
This year, Beijing Jiaotong University, Beijing University of Science and Technology, Beijing University of Posts and Telecommunications, Beijing Forestry University and Beijing University of Chemical Technology jointly issued the 2020 enrollment policy to cancel the professional grade difference.
What is the meaning of professional grade difference and what is the significance in voluntary filing?
There are three ways of professional allocation rules
Experts remind that before filling in the volunteer form, you must carefully read the "Enrollment Regulations" of your favorite school and understand the admission rules of colleges and universities, including the ratio of file transfer and the rules of professional distribution.
Professional allocation rules refer to three ways of professional admission: professional priority, score priority and professional grade difference after the transfer of colleges and universities.
The specific method used by colleges and universities will be specified in the Admissions Charter.
However, there are also some colleges and universities whose admission principle is to give priority to the total score, and there is no grade difference between majors.
That is to say, candidates within the admission range will be queued up according to the total score. When the score does not reach the first professional voluntary admission score line, it will be seen whether it has reached the second professional voluntary admission score line, and so on until the last professional volunteer is admitted. There is no grade difference between the professional volunteers.
The so-called "professional grade difference" means that when colleges and universities arrange candidates' majors, they determine the admission majors of volunteer candidates of different majors according to one or several score values published in the enrollment regulations. This score value is the "professional grade difference."
That is, the score difference between the first professional volunteer and the non-first professional volunteer in colleges and universities, and the grade difference scores between the professional volunteers, such as 3 points, 2 points, 1 point, etc.
For example.
Suppose student Xiaoming applied for college A and scored 560 points. His professional wishes are: computer, international trade, automation, mechanical engineering, and e-commerce. The professional admission of college A adopts the method of professional grade difference, which is divided into 2 points, 1 point, 1 point, and 0 point.
In the professional allocation, if Xiaoming's first professional volunteer meets the professional admission requirements and the major has a planned balance, then Xiaoming is admitted to the "computer" major; If the computer is not admitted, his score will be subtracted by 2 points, and the score of 558 points will be sorted with the candidates who volunteer to apply for "international trade" in the first major to determine whether they meet the professional admission conditions; If it is still not satisfied, the score will be subtracted by 1 point (that is, 557 points) for the "automatic" admission of the third professional volunteer; If it is still not satisfied, the score will be subtracted by 1 point (that is, 556 points) for admission to the fourth major. If the follow-up major still cannot meet its professional wishes, the score will not be reduced, and so on.
Different universities have different professional grade differences
With the popularization of parallel volunteering, many colleges and universities have cancelled the professional grade difference, but some colleges and universities still retain this method this year. According to the "enrollment regulations" published by various universities, more than 20 universities have set up professional grade difference this year.
For example, Sichuan Agricultural University, Shandong University of Science and Technology, Heilongjiang University of Traditional Chinese Medicine, Jiangsu University of Science and Technology, Jiangxi Normal University, Chengdu Medical College, Northeast Electric Power University, Jimei University, Nanjing Medical University, Nanjing University of Technology, Ningxia University, Shandong University of Technology, China Civil Aviation Flight College, etc.
In these colleges and universities, each university has different professional grades.
Some colleges and universities have a grade difference in each major, such as Ningxia University. Candidates whose files have been submitted to the university will be admitted according to the order in which candidates fill in their professional volunteers by 1 point in turn.
Some universities have set up different professional grades between different majors.
For example, Jimei University, the total score of professional volunteer difference is 4 points, that is, the difference between the first professional volunteer and other professional volunteers is 3 points, there is no difference between other professional volunteers, which is regarded as parallel volunteer, and the difference between other professional volunteers and transfer professional volunteers is 1 point.
When filling in the volunteer form, candidates and parents must carefully read the admission policy of the reported school to see if there is a professional grade difference and what is the form of the grade difference. While fully considering the score, they should also reasonably analyze the school and major to be selected. If the college clearly adopts the grade difference method for admission in the enrollment charter, candidates should pay attention to the gradient between the majors when choosing a major to improve the admission probability.
